    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:ccf614e9-688b-4956-91fc-09767a6dde49",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 33-year-old woman who arrives to urgent care looking tired, mildly uncomfortable, and frequently shifting in her chair because of suprapubic pressure and urinary urgency. She is casually dressed in office clothes, keeps a water bottle in hand, and appears embarrassed by how often she has needed the restroom over the last 24 hours. Her speech is clear and organized, but she winces slightly when describing burning with urination and says the symptoms came on quickly over the past two days. She is afebrile to low-grade febrile in appearance, without looking toxic or severely ill.\n\nShe works full-time as a project coordinator for a marketing firm, spending long hours at a desk and often delaying bathroom breaks during busy deadlines. Outside of work, {patientName} enjoys yoga classes, weekend walks with friends, and caring for a small herb garden on her apartment balcony. She is socially active, lives with her partner, and has a supportive circle of close friends and family nearby. She drinks coffee daily, tries to stay hydrated, and occasionally has a glass of wine on weekends.\n\nHer current symptoms include dysuria, urinary frequency, urgency, and dull lower abdominal discomfort. She denies flank pain, shaking chills, or severe nausea, which makes upper urinary tract involvement less likely. She notes that she has had one prior bladder infection several years ago and recognized the familiar burning sensation quickly. She is concerned because the discomfort is affecting sleep and concentration at work.\n\n{patientName}'s lifestyle includes regular exercise and generally balanced meals, though she admits stress can lead to irregular hydration and prolonged periods without voiding. She is sexually active in a monogamous relationship and reports symptom onset after a particularly busy week with poor fluid intake. She does not smoke or use illicit drugs. Overall, she appears like a young otherwise healthy adult with an acute but uncomplicated urinary tract infection causing distress rather than systemic instability."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:929428cc-1f45-4925-8c6a-5bc7349bcf40",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no major chronic medical conditions and no history of diabetes, kidney stones, or structural urinary tract disease. She reports one prior uncomplicated urinary tract infection about 4 years ago that resolved with oral antibiotics and did not require hospitalization. She has never had pyelonephritis and has no history of recurrent multidrug-resistant infections.\n\nShe has no significant surgical history except for a cesarean section in 2018. She currently uses a levonorgestrel intrauterine device for contraception that was inserted in 2021. She is not pregnant by history. She denies tobacco and recreational drug use and drinks alcohol only occasionally. Relevant contributing factors include recent poor hydration, prolonged intervals between voiding during work, and recent sexual activity.\n\nShe has a medication allergy to penicillin that caused urticaria as a teenager. Family history is notable for type 2 diabetes in her mother and hypertension in her father. She is independent in activities of daily living and generally active, with yoga and walking several times per week."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
